{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505409"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:30:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:30:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2438"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2438"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.35,0.25,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2438"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116307"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2438"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2438"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98303"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1922"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49917"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116307"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of worsening left iliac fossa pain. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He lives in his own home with his wife.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 84/min, blood pressure 135/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. There is tenderness in the left iliac fossa without guarding or rebound. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal a white cell count of 10.6 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.5-11.0), C-reactive protein of 14 mg/L (\u0026lt;5), and normal renal and liver function tests. A computed tomography scan confirms acute diverticulitis with a 5 cm segment of sigmoid colon affected, pericolic fat stranding, and thickening of the bowel wall. There is no evidence of abscess, perforation, or fistula formation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Analgesics as required and outpatient review","Oral antibiotics and review in clinic in four days","Intravenous antibiotics and admission to hospital","Colonoscopy within the next week","Laparoscopy and peritoneal washout"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with uncomplicated diverticulitis, characterised by inflammation of colonic diverticula without evidence of complications such as abscess, perforation, fistula, or obstruction. Current evidence supports a more conservative approach to management than was previously standard.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnalgesics as required and outpatient review\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for this patient with uncomplicated diverticulitis who has minimal systemic symptoms, no significant comorbidities, and adequate social support. Recent studies have shown that many patients with uncomplicated diverticulitis can be safely managed without antibiotics. The patient should be advised to maintain adequate hydration and can gradually advance his diet as tolerated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotics and review in clinic in four days\u003C/strong\u003E would have been the standard approach until recently. However, multiple randomised controlled trials have now demonstrated that antibiotics do not significantly improve outcomes in uncomplicated diverticulitis in otherwise healthy patients. Antibiotics should be reserved for patients with systemic signs of infection, immunosuppression, or significant comorbidities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics and admission to hospital\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for complicated diverticulitis (with abscess, perforation, or fistula), significant systemic symptoms, inability to tolerate oral intake, severe pain requiring parenteral analgesia, or inadequate social support. This patient has none of these features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy within the next week\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate during the acute phase of diverticulitis due to the risk of perforation. If colonoscopy is indicated to exclude other pathology (particularly in patients over 50 years with a first presentation), it should be delayed until 4-6 weeks after the acute episode has resolved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopy and peritoneal washout\u003C/strong\u003E would only be considered in cases of perforated diverticulitis with purulent or fecal peritonitis. This patient has uncomplicated diverticulitis without evidence of perforation, making surgical intervention unnecessary and potentially harmful.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of uncomplicated diverticulitis can be managed on an outpatient basis without antibiotics.","Antibiotics in diverticulitis treatment should be considered selectively for patients with comorbidities, systemic infection, or immunosuppression.","Colonoscopy should be delayed in diverticulitis cases until after the acute inflammatory episode has resolved."],"references":["Young-Fadok TM. Diverticulitis. N Eng J Med 2018;379:1635-42. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30354951/","Sacks OA, Hall J. Management of Diverticulitis: A Review. JAMA Surg. 2024 Jun 1;159(6):696-703. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38630452/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98303"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2438"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98303"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T10:57:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:58:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2438"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116307"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"